Signed-off-by: Waldemar Quevedo <wally@synadia.com>

make api more consistent with other clients

This commit is an attempt to make the api of this client more closely
match the api of nats clients in other languages. Below is a non
exhaustive list of the changes made.

- Return subscriptions from `subscribe()` instead of a subscription id
- Allow iterating over messages in subscription with `async for`. To use, don't specify a callback when subscribing
- Move `unsubscribe()` and `drain(sid=sid)` to the subscription class
- Remove `publish_request()`, `publish()` now has a `reply` kwarg
- Remove `auto_unsubscribe()`, `subscribe()` already had a kwarg for this
- Remove support for executing synchronous callbacks
  - Remove `subscribe_async()`
  - Remove `is_async` kwarg from `subscribe()`
- Remove support for executing callbacks as tasks
- Remove multiple response functionality from `request()`
- Remove `timed_request()`, name is very misleading as all requests are timed. This was really old style requests, moved to a kwarg of `request()` called `old_style`
- Made connection context manager async
- Various internal code reoganizations
- Various doc cleanups
- Cleaned up example code

Update readme examples

Modernizes the way we package and distribute nats.py by using PEP621 (#341)

* Modernizes the way nats.py is packaged with PEP-621 [1]

Modern Python packages can contain a pyproject.toml file, first
introduced in PEP 518 and later expanded in PEP 517, PEP 621 and PEP 660 [2].

Starting with PEP 621, the Python community selected pyproject.toml as a
standard way of specifying project metadata [3]. Setuptools has adopted this
standard [4] and will use the information contained in this file as an input
in the build process.

This patch propose o adopt this standard into the nats project to modernize
the way this library is packaged and distributed.

This changes propose to move stored data from setup.py to the
pyproject.toml file by respecting supported keys and sections.

These changes propose to use setuptools as backend to create
distribution packages, because it is a well know backend with a long
story and well maintained and it is the one I'm used to use and so
that's the one I know the well.

Also you should notice that these changes propose to rename our readme
file. All-uppercase letters stand out and make the file easily visible which
makes sense because it is probably the first thing a new user would want
to look at. The file's name is generally written in uppercase [5]. Lowercase
filenames are more common files. Also it will standardize the naming
conventions with others files like `LICENSE`, `CODE_OF_CONDUCT`, etc.

These changes can be tested by using the following commands:
```
$ python -m pip install --upgrade build
$ python -m build
```

[1] https://peps.python.org/pep-0621/
[2] https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/tutorials/packaging-projects/
[3] https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/reference/build-system/pyproject-toml/
[4] https://setuptools.pypa.io/en/latest/userguide/pyproject_config.html
[5] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/README

Also:

* Adds some gitignore rules

* Pluralizes folder name

This folder contains more than one script so these changes proposes
to pluralize its name to better reflect this aspect.
